## How NeuronCore profiling works

NeuronCores execute *compiled graphs* (NEFFs). You cannot profile work that never reached the device â€” so first confirm the model actually runs on a NeuronCore (compiled graphs executing on-device), not on CPU. Profiling is two steps: **capture** a hardware profile around a live workload, then **analyze** it.

## Capturing a profile (shell â€” long-running, do this first)

1. Read `main.py` and the benchmark `--help` output to understand how the candidate is exercised.
2. Stop any stale candidate processes from previous attempts.
3. Pre-warm â€” the first `neuronx-cc` compile of each graph shape takes minutes; warm it so the capture reflects steady state, not compilation.
4. Capture around a benchmark load using the `capture` MCP tool (or shell):
   ```
   python neuron_profiler/analyze_neuron.py capture \
     --out-dir /tmp/neuronprof \
     --workload "<benchmark command>"
   ```
   Use any domain-specific capture recipe above when one is provided{% if bench_path is defined and bench_path %}, otherwise discover a short representative command from `uv run python {{ bench_path }}/benchmark.py --help`{% endif %}. `capture` wraps `neuron-explorer inspect`, which runs the workload and writes a system + device profile (NTFF) plus the NEFF into the out-dir. If it reports **no NTFF/NEFF produced**, the candidate is not executing on the NeuronCore â€” record that as the headline finding.

## Analysis toolkit â€” `vibeserve-neuron-profiler` MCP tools OR shell

If the `vibeserve-neuron-profiler` MCP server is attached to this round, call its tools directly. Otherwise shell out to the same subcommand on `python neuron_profiler/analyze_neuron.py`.

| MCP tool | Shell equivalent | Purpose |
| -------- | ---------------- | ------- |
| `capture(workload, out_dir)` | `analyze_neuron.py capture --workload "<cmd>" --out-dir <dir>` | Run workload under `neuron-explorer inspect`. |
| `summary(report)` | `analyze_neuron.py summary <dir>` | Engine utilization + top ops + DMA. Start here. |
| `summary_json(report)` | `analyze_neuron.py summary-json <dir>` | Same, machine-readable. |
| `operators(report)` | `analyze_neuron.py operators <dir>` | Per-operator/instruction breakdown. |
| `dma(report)` | `analyze_neuron.py dma <dir>` | Raw DMA trace. |
| `view(report, output_format)` | `analyze_neuron.py view <dir> --output-format <fmt>` | Raw `neuron-explorer view` passthrough. |

Start with `summary`, then drill into `operators` / `dma` as needed.

